# To define the time you can provide concrete values for # minute (m), hour (h), day of month (dom), month (mon), # and day of week (dow) or use '*' in these fields (for 'any').
#
# Notice that tasks will be started based on the cron's system
# daemon's notion of time and timezones.
#
# Output of the crontab jobs (including errors) is sent through
# email to the user the crontab file belongs to (unless redirected).
#
# For example, you can run a backup of all your user accounts
# at 5 a.m every week with: # 0 5 ** 1 tar -zcf /var/backups/home.tgz /home/
#
# For more information see the manual pages of crontab(5) and cron (8)
#
# mh dom mon dow command

# Backup System
0 * * * * /home/$USER/.dotfiles/backup.sh

0 0 * * * /usr/bin/clamscan --exclude-dir=/home/$USER/.clamtk/viruses --exclude-dir=smb4k --exclude-dir=/run/user/$USER/gvfs --exclude-dir=/home/$USER/.gvfs --exclude-dir=.thunderbird --exclude-dir=.mozilla-thunderbird --exclude-dir=.evolution --exclude-dir=Mail --exclude-dir=kmail -i -r /home/$USER --log="$HOME/.clamtk/history/$(date +\%b-\%d-\%Y).log" 2>/dev/null # clamtk-scan

